A team runs a Go Temporal Cloud worker fleet behind a corporate firewall. They configure mTLS using `tls.LoadX509KeyPair` and connect to `yournamespace.a2fx6.tmprl.cloud:7233`. After a routine cert rotation, half the workers begin failing to start with TLS handshake errors, while the other half continue polling normally. The team notices that the failing workers were NOT restarted — only new deployments got the rotated certs. Which of the following best explains this behavior and its relationship to Temporal's worker registration model?

```go
cert, err := tls.LoadX509KeyPair(clientCertPath, clientKeyPath)
temporalClient, err := client.Dial(client.Options{
    HostPort:  hostPort,
    Namespace: namespace,
    ConnectionOptions: client.ConnectionOptions{
        TLS: &tls.Config{Certificates: []tls.Certificate{cert}},
    },
})
yourWorker := worker.New(temporalClient, "my-task-queue", worker.Options{})
```

A .NET team uses the dependency injection approach to run a Temporal worker with a scoped `IMyDatabaseClient`. During a rolling deployment, they briefly have two worker versions running simultaneously on the same task queue — one with `MyWorkflowV1` registered and one with `MyWorkflowV2` registered (a renamed workflow type). A new workflow execution is started for `MyWorkflowV2` while both versions are live. What happens when a `MyWorkflowV1`-only worker polls and receives the `MyWorkflowV2` workflow task?

```csharp
// Old worker
ctx.AddHostedTemporalWorker("localhost:7233", "default", "order-queue")
   .AddScopedActivities<MyActivities>()
   .AddWorkflow<MyWorkflowV1>();

// New worker
ctx.AddHostedTemporalWorker("localhost:7233", "default", "order-queue")
   .AddScopedActivities<MyActivities>()
   .AddWorkflow<MyWorkflowV2>();
```
